@startuml
title casbinjs/react - Component View and Responsibility Boundaries

skinparam componentStyle rectangle
skinparam shadowing false

actor ReactConsumer as Consumer

package "Consumer App" {
  component "App-owned Data Fetching" as Fetching
  component "UI Components" as UI
}

package "casbinjs/react" {
  interface "useCasbin()" as UseCasbin
  interface "useCan() / useCanAny() / useCanAll()" as UsePermissionHooks
  component "CasbinProvider" as Provider
  component "React Context" as Context
}

package "casbinjs/core" {
  interface "Authorizer" as Authorizer
}

database "External Endpoint / Data Source" as Endpoint

Consumer <-- UI
Endpoint ---> Fetching : policy snapshot

Fetching --> Provider : pass authorizer or options
Provider -> Context : provide authz state
Provider ---> Authorizer : create / use authorizer
UseCasbin <-- Context : consume authorizer state
UsePermissionHooks <-- UseCasbin : derive React-friendly permission state
UI <-- UseCasbin : addPolicy / removePolicy / replacePolicies
UI <-- UsePermissionHooks : allowed / isLoading / error

note top of Fetching
Application-owned fetching.
Not part of casbinjs/react.
end note

note bottom of Provider
casbinjs/react owns:
- provider wiring
- context integration
- React-ready hooks
- async readiness / error state
end note

note bottom of UsePermissionHooks
Hook-level async wrappers for permission checks.
Avoid forcing consumers to write useEffect
for common can / canAny / canAll usage.
end note

note top of Authorizer
casbinjs/core owns:
- vanilla-ready authorizer contract
- delegation to casbin-core
end note
@enduml
